[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] In signal processing, **sampling** is the reduction of a continuous-time signal to a discrete-time signal.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] A common example is the conversion of a sound wave to a sequence of "samples".
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] A **sample** is a value of the signal at a point in time and/or space; this definition differs from the term's usage in statistics, which refers to a set of such values.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] A **sampler** is a subsystem or operation that extracts samples from a continuous signal.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] A theoretical **ideal sampler** produces samples equivalent to the instantaneous value of the continuous signal at the desired points.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The original signal can be reconstructed from a sequence of samples, up to the Nyquist limit, by passing the sequence of samples through a reconstruction filter.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Functions of space, time, or any other dimension can be sampled, and similarly in two or more dimensions.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] For functions that vary with time, let $s(t)$ be a continuous function (or "signal") to be sampled, and let sampling be performed by measuring the value of the continuous function every T seconds, which is called the **sampling interval** or **sampling period**.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The **sampling frequency** or **sampling rate**, $f_{s}$ , is the average number of samples obtained in one second, thus $f_{s}=1/T$ , with the unit *samples per second*, sometimes referred to as hertz, for example 48 kHz is 48,000 *samples per second*.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Reconstructing a continuous function from samples is done by interpolation algorithms.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula is mathematically equivalent to an ideal low-pass filter whose input is a sequence of Dirac delta functions that are modulated (multiplied) by the sample values.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] When the time interval between adjacent samples is a constant $(T)$ , the sequence of delta functions is called a Dirac comb.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Mathematically, the modulated Dirac comb is equivalent to the product of the comb function with $s(t)$ .
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] That mathematical abstraction is sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Most sampled signals are not simply stored and reconstructed.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction is a common measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] That fidelity is reduced when $s(t)$ contains frequency components whose cycle length (period) is less than 2 sample intervals (see *Aliasing*).
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The corresponding frequency limit, in *cycles per second* (hertz), is $0.5$ cycle/sample × $f_{s}$ samples/second = $f_{s}/2$ , known as the Nyquist frequency of the sampler.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Therefore, $s(t)$ is usually the output of a low-pass filter, functionally known as an *anti-aliasing filter*.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Without an anti-aliasing filter, frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency will influence the samples in a way that is misinterpreted by the interpolation process.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] In practice, the continuous signal is sampled using an analog-to-digital converter (ADC), a device with various physical limitations.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] This results in deviations from the theoretically perfect reconstruction, collectively referred to as distortion.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Although the use of oversampling can completely eliminate aperture error and aliasing by shifting them out of the passband, this technique cannot be practically used above a few GHz, and may be prohibitively expensive at much lower frequencies.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Furthermore, while oversampling can reduce quantization error and non-linearity, it cannot eliminate these entirely.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Consequently, practical ADCs at audio frequencies typically do not exhibit aliasing or aperture error, and are not limited by quantization error.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] At RF and microwave frequencies, where oversampling is impractical and filters are expensive, aperture error, quantization error and aliasing can be significant limitations.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Jitter, noise, and quantization are often analyzed by modeling them as random errors added to the sample values.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Integration and zero-order hold effects can be analyzed as a form of low-pass filtering.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The non-linearities of either ADC or DAC are analyzed by replacing the ideal linear function mapping with a proposed nonlinear function.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Digital audio systems typically employ pulse-code modulation (PCM) to encode sound as a series of discrete samples of the electrical level of an analog audio signal.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Analog signals are captured (encoded) as PCM samples in analog-to-digital conversion (ADC), and reproduced (decoded) using digital-to-analog conversion (DAC).
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The encoding used for the storage and transmission of digitised sound data within the system may differ.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] When it is necessary to capture audio covering the entire 20–20,000 Hz range of human hearing such as when recording music or many types of acoustic events, audio waveforms are typically sampled at 44.1 kHz (CD), 48 kHz, 88.2 kHz, or 96 kHz.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] The approximately double-rate requirement is a consequence of the Nyquist theorem.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Sampling rates higher than about 50 kHz to 60 kHz cannot supply more usable information for human listeners.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Early professional audio equipment manufacturers chose sampling rates in the region of 40 to 50 kHz for this reason.
[src:profiling-continuous/sampling-signal-processing] Conversely, ultrasonic sounds may interact with and modulate the audible part of the frequency spectrum (intermodulation distortion), *degrading* the fidelity.
